Stream.concat() in Java

Stream.concat() is a static method used to combine two streams into a single stream.

👉 The elements of the first stream come first, followed by the elements of the second stream.

Method Signature
static <T> Stream<T> concat(
        Stream<? extends T> a,
        Stream<? extends T> b
)
Parameters
a → first stream
b → second stream
Return Value

Returns a new Stream containing all elements from both streams.

Basic Example
Stream<String> stream1 =
        Stream.of("Apple", "Banana");

Stream<String> stream2 =
        Stream.of("Orange", "Mango");

Stream<String> result =
        Stream.concat(stream1, stream2);

result.forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

Apple
Banana
Orange
Mango
How concat() Works
Stream 1:
Apple
Banana

+

Stream 2:
Orange
Mango

↓

New Stream:
Apple
Banana
Orange
Mango
Example with Numbers
Stream<Integer> first =
        Stream.of(1, 2, 3);

Stream<Integer> second =
        Stream.of(4, 5, 6);

Stream.concat(first, second)
      .forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

1
2
3
4
5
6
Using concat() with Collections
List<String> fruits =
        List.of("Apple", "Banana");

List<String> vegetables =
        List.of("Carrot", "Potato");

Stream.concat(
        fruits.stream(),
        vegetables.stream()
)
.forEach(System.out::println);
Using concat() with Other Stream Operations
Stream.concat(
        Stream.of(1, 2, 3),
        Stream.of(4, 5, 6)
)
.filter(x -> x % 2 == 0)
.forEach(System.out::println);

Output:

2
4
6
Important Notes
Streams can only be used once
Stream<String> stream1 =
        Stream.of("A", "B");

Stream<String> stream2 =
        Stream.of("C", "D");

Stream<String> result =
        Stream.concat(stream1, stream2);

result.forEach(System.out::println);

// stream1.forEach(...); ❌ Error

After a stream is consumed, it cannot be reused.

concat() vs addAll()
addAll()
list1.addAll(list2);
modifies the original collection
works with collections
Stream.concat()
Stream.concat(stream1, stream2);
does not modify collections
creates a new stream
works only with streams
Time Complexity

If the first stream has n elements and the second has m elements:

O(n + m)

because every element is processed once.

Common Interview Questions
Is concat() a Stream method?

❌ No.

It is a static method of the Stream class.

Does concat() modify the original streams?

❌ No.

It creates a new stream.

How many streams can concat() combine?

✅ Only two at a time.

To combine more, you can nest calls:

Stream.concat(
    Stream.concat(stream1, stream2),
    stream3
);
Summary
Stream.concat() combines two streams into one.
It is a static method of the Stream class.
The original streams are not modified.
The elements of the first stream are followed by the elements of the second stream.
Returns a new Stream.
Time complexity is O(n + m).
